  <h2 id="epc">Why the EPC cross-trip is not a model defect</h2>
  <p>
    This is the issue most likely to be misread, so it is worth stating plainly. If you load
    the OPDA ontology into a generic reasoner running <em>full</em> RDFS or OWL — one that
    applies <code>rdfs:domain</code> entailment — and you assert an
    <code>opda:EPCCertificate</code> that carries <code>currentEnergyRating</code>, that
    reasoner will infer the certificate <em>is</em> an <code>opda:Property</code>, because
    <code>currentEnergyRating</code> is declared with <code>rdfs:domain opda:Property</code>.
    That inference is wrong: an EPC certificate is a document <em>about</em> a property, not
    the property itself.
  </p>
  <p>
    OPDA does not make that inference. The Safe-Group closure adopted in
    <a href="/modelling/odr/odr-0025">ODR-0025</a> (§R7) <strong>deliberately excludes
    domain and range rules</strong>. The seven frozen rules cover subclass, subproperty,
    inverse, symmetric and transitive entailment — the relations whose closure the author
    actually wants — and nothing that would manufacture a spurious class membership from a
    property's declared domain. The round-trip exemplars are validated against
    <em>this</em> closure, and they pass. So the cross-trip is a <strong>consumer-side
    trap</strong> (and a modelling smell worth knowing about), not a defect in OPDA's
    graph, and it does not block <code>draft → accepted</code>. The provenance for this
    ruling is on the <a href="/ontology/provenance#this-reference">Decision provenance</a>
    page.
  </p>

  <h2 id="thin">Why thin profiles are by design</h2>
  <p>
    "A form IS its SHACL overlay" (<a href="/modelling/odr/odr-0010">ODR-0010</a>). But a
    PDTF form is mostly questions whose answers are A/B/C/D/E/F treatments — carried by
    <code>dct:subject</code> and a JSON-pointer <code>dct:source</code> — not Category-G
    substantive attributes that bind as per-leaf <code>sh:path</code> shapes. A profile that
    binds only its Category-G leaves and GAP-registers the rest is therefore the
    <strong>ratified outcome, not an omission</strong> (session-034). A "thin" profile that
    binds zero per-leaf shapes (<code>oc1</code>, <code>llc1</code>, <code>tf</code>, and
    others) is correct: the leaves it would otherwise bind are register extracts or
    free-text, and the GAP register records exactly which leaves are unbound and why. The
    live profile counts and the bound/thin split are on the
    <a href="/ontology#counts">overview</a> and the bake-off's custom-layer rendering.
  </p>

  <h2 id="ruleset">Why the ruleset is not an OWL 2 RL reasoner</h2>
  <p>
    An earlier framing risked implying that <code>config/opda-rdfs-plus.rules</code> was an
    OWL 2 RL profile reasoner. It is not, and <a href="/modelling/odr/odr-0029">ODR-0029</a>
    R5 resolved this by renaming the artefact and giving it an honest header. The ruleset is
    a <strong>sound but RL-incomplete</strong> fragment: it implements seven of the OWL-RL
    rules and deliberately omits domain/range, equality (<code>owl:sameAs</code>),
    functional-property and equivalence reasoning. Soundness means everything it derives is
    valid; RL-incompleteness means it does not derive everything OWL 2 RL would — which is
    the point, because the omitted rules are exactly the ones that would produce the EPC
    cross-trip and spurious <code>owl:sameAs</code> collapses. The rule logic is now frozen.
  </p>

  <p class="muted">
    Related: <a href="/ontology/provenance">Decision provenance</a> (the governing records),
    <a href="/ontology/usage">Consume the ontology</a> (the <code>advanced=True</code>
    validation recipe), and the <a href="/ontology/bake-off">Tool bake-off</a> (the custom
    layer that emits the GAP register).
  </p>
</Layout>
